      <dateline>TRENTON</dateline>
      <abstract>
        <p>New Jersey Senate committee approves two bills that would increase charges against hit-and-run drivers from misdemeanors to felonies with mandatory jail time (New Jersey Daily Briefing) (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>A Senate committee yesterday approved two bills that would increase charges against hit-and-run drivers from misdemeanors to felonies with mandatory jail time.</p>
        <p>Anyone leaving an accident scene in which a victim died would be subject to a one-year prison sentence; if the victim suffered a serious injury, the offender would be subject to six months in jail. Both offenses would carry fines of up to $7,500.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>A Senate committee yesterday approved two bills that would increase charges against hit-and-run drivers from misdemeanors to felonies with mandatory jail time.</p>
        <p>Anyone leaving an accident scene in which a victim died would be subject to a one-year prison sentence; if the victim suffered a serious injury, the offender would be subject to six months in jail. Both offenses would carry fines of up to $7,500.</p>
        <p>The proposed legislation was sponsored by two Republican Senators, John J. Matheussen of Turnersville and Jack G. Sinagra of Edison, whose districts had four hit-and-run deaths since 1994. The legislation is awaiting full Senate approval.</p>
        <p>NEW JERSEY DAILY BRIEFING</p>
      </block>
